social_posts.post_text: Dear @snagtights .

TW: Loss/Mental Health

There is a blurred line between needing to remember you and wanting to forget.

To have a moment where I no longer count the days you have been gone from this world, but at the same time, not wanting to face the inevitable truth.
I do not want to forget you.
But I fear as the sound of your laughter fades, so does the feeling of being able to hold onto all of the remnants of you left I have tried so hard to save.
Knowing no matter what path I choose will hurt, letting go is a kind of pain I do not know if I will ever be ready for, but eventually be a decision I will have to make. 
I do not want to forget you. 
And even though remembering you gives me brief contentment, missing you brings a burden of guilt and an overwhelming selfish need to try to live my life without you. 
Life, however, is never that simple. 
A part of me died along with you while a piece of you survived within me.
I do not want to forget you, but I could never be whole without you.

Happy Birthday River.
02/05/2001 - 01/07/2019

In need of financial medical assistance. 

My partner does not and cannot afford medical insurance. We have applied multiple times and they do not qualify. They have also missed a lot of work because of their struggle with their health, but also, it has not helped not being able to afford their medications on top of the continued shortage of ADHD meds. 

I am really struggling right now between the recent loss of Basil and trying to convince my partner to go in to at the very least talk to their doctor about what is going on and if there is a possible solution. However, just to see their primary it will cost between $200-300. 

And we just do not have that.

Please help us. 
And thank you.

Sometimes you need to start over more than once in your life because you know you deserve better and continue to want more for yourself.

Here is to turning 33.

Something that I have learned is that when looking for advice on brands and what fits true to size, the best people to go to are those in larger bodies.  And I say this because they actually know what works and what doesn’t in most sizes as they’ve been that size themselves at some point rather than someone who has always been on the smaller end of the spectrum and assumes that because a look has some stretch that it will fit someone who is bigger properly. 

Most of the time it doesn’t.
Follow and listen to larger bodies.

There is not enough representation and acceptance of large fat bodies above size 26, so here you go.

I will not deny that sometimes looking in the mirror is hard. 

Internalized fatphobia is ingrained in every fat person including myself and we all have bad days where we revert to old habits and it’s often just to protect ourselves. 

Because fat people are constantly censured and who doesn’t want to step back and take a break from having to deal with people who refuse to treat you like a human being or who continue to criticize you everyday for not being ashamed of your own body and just trying to live your life?

And although it is okay to have those feelings at times, it is acknowledging that they are problematic and continuing to try and overcome that mindset rather than let it be an excuse to harm yourself and others that makes a difference.

Don’t stop trying.

Do you ever just go for a car ride, the radio is playing, the sun is setting, and all of a sudden you are transported into the middle of a sad cinematic movie called your life? 

I need to stop waiting to write the character arc I was meant to have.

Happy Pride, but especially to all my fellow Queer fatties. I love you.

I have reposted this because it is as valid today as it was years ago when I originally shared it.

People who say you can do anything you want to, you just have to work hard enough, are the same people who grew up with money, who have had the privilege and access of opportunity and do not understand that working hard was never the problem.

I was five years old when a couple of kids were bullying me and calling me fat before throwing rocks at me while I ran home crying.

How old were you when you started to learn what it meant to be fat and perhaps how you have redefined the meaning for yourself?

Movement has been difficult, more so each day for me. Most days I spend my time in bed or in the bathroom in pain and it has taken a toll on my mental health. I feel like I need to push myself to do something, anything, and my body continues to fail me. I know that it hasn’t truly failed and it is a part of my disability, but I cannot help, but feel helpless at times. Even after years of dealing with my health, I am still not used to not being as able as I used to be. Everyday I work on overcoming those internalized thoughts. I am not perfect.

There is a local YMCA that I have tried to visit at least once a week for the past month to use the pool, a place where I can move without being in so much pain, but provides a lot of resistance. The problem is I cannot drive and or sometimes my health will simply not allow me to make it. My partner works and has their own health problems as well. I would really like to go a couple times a week if possible, but I would have to use our local cab and it is $7 a round trip. Most of you know we are struggling just to get by, but if you’d like to help make that happen for me, that would help me greatly, both physically and mentally.

I have to be honest, I haven’t had the most healthy or consistent relationship with pleasure. 

I learned early on that fat people were made to feel like they did not deserve pleasure and for awhile I truly believed that. I constantly looked for affection in all the wrong places because any was better than none in my mind. Even if it was the worst kind. 

It took over a decade to really come to terms that I was more than some THING, but SOMEONE who deserved better. Not just from others, but from myself. 

To be able to now experience pleasure in any degree that does not necessarily require the bedroom like simply enjoying a cheap slice of pepperoni pizza at a park near the water while my partner is massaging my legs, gives the kind of happiness that we are ALL entitled to have.

But also the recognition that I, as a fat person, am deserving. A reminder that fat people deserve pleasure too.

@vush_official sent this amazing package over for my partner and I that included a set of cards or “Curiosity Cues” that allowed us to have a little fun and reminded us of what intimacy and pleasure meant for us. Please check them out and use code 20CASEYS to get a 20% discount on the We Come First kit! #ad #vushpartner

I remember my ex-stepmother bringing me to the older women’s section of the store to look at one pieces. I remember seeing and hating all the prints that reminded me of something my grandmother might have worn. It made me feel more self conscious about myself than I already was and I started to tear up when I could not find anything that I liked. My ex-stepmother made it clear these were the only options they had for someone my size. She didn’t even bother bringing me over to the kids section to see if there was anything there. All I wanted was to be an eleven year old kid and wear something that was meant for me and I never got that chance.

And as a size 30-32 today, I still struggle to find a swimsuit that not only fits, but is really meant for me. As much as I talk everyday about it being okay to be fat, there are still things even at the age of 33 that I am still working on. However, seeing @jordallenhall in that aster @you.swim bikini and looking HOT if I might add, has really inspired and made me WANT to wear something different than just a basic one piece. So thank you for that. That is now on my to-do list.

Meet our newest addition to our family, Truffle. Currently fostering her (and hoping to eventually adopt) from our local humane society @couleehumane . She’s had some stomach problems and was on some antibiotics when we first got her, but now she seems to be doing a lot better besides some gas. She and Nutmeg have really become best of friends and we couldn’t be happier with our growing little family. 

Speaking about our local shelter, it has been overwhelmed with taking in animals, especially cats and kittens (over 300) and could really use some cat food and supplies. If you are able to help, the link is in my bio that will show you how you can donate!

All plus size stores, all stores that carry and cater to plus sizes, at the BARE MINIMUM, should be providing up to a 6X at this point. 

Going up to a size 22, or even a size 24, was being done by brands over five years ago. You weren’t inclusive then and you aren’t inclusive now.
Today’s advice: Drink your orange juice and be weird.

No matter your struggles. 
No matter your income.
No matter.

You deserve to treat yourself.
You deserve to live your life. 
You deserve more than surviving. 

And if people decide to judge you for going “outside your means,” call that classist and capitalist behavior out.
There’s nothing butter than fat.
When anyone starts off a conversation with “fat bodies shouldn’t,” there is no such thing as good intentions.

I am not perfect. I struggle every day and wonder if things would really be easier if I wasn’t my size. Then I remind myself how no one should have to change to be treated like any other person. 

Your life being hard has nothing to do with your size and everything to do with society’s anti-fatness.

#ad | @torrid was the first store at 18 that I did not have to go into a back corner of a third floor department store to find something that simply only fit me.

At age 33, Torrid is still a significant staple for me, but as a size 6X, the opportunity to find and try on clothes in store is no longer an option. As convenient and accessible as it can be to order online, and it is especially as someone who is disabled, I miss the experience I once had the first time I saw Torrid. 

I felt seen. 

So here is my plea as your #torridambassador 
Please bring back all sizes onto the floor. 

With all the love,

Your Fat Community

Please tell me how I should be inspired by your plus size look when the clothes you wear do not go past a size 24. 

How inspired should I be as someone who is a size 30 and still struggling to get the same access as you, not even focusing on the privileges of straight sizes, but on those in my own community who have benefited from that proximity and stay silent as the people with larger bodies ask for the bare minimum. 

Because every time I see someone asking that of us, I am reminded how little inspired the majority of our community is to liberate and include the rest.

Your life being hard has nothing to do with your size and everything to do with society’s anti-fatness.

Inspired by the beautiful #gifted Azul set from @feltandfat and our local restaurant @lovechildrestaurant pappardelle dish, here is to sharing my love with you all. From cooking to plating to eating, food is one of my biggest passions and what truly fulFILLS me. Please enjoy.
It is giving 90’s femme in the best way.

I recently found out that my father’s biological relatives are Persian and that a part of me is also Persian and with food being my love language, I wanted to share and celebrate with a dish. My grandmother (father’s adoptive mother) would make her Scandinavian rice pudding, especially during the holidays and when I was looking up recipes for inspiration, I found one. It was perfect, except I did not have any edible rosebuds, so I used dried cranberries instead. 

•

Sholeh Zard or otherwise known as Persian saffron and rosewater rice pudding topped with cinnamon, pistachio nuts, and dried cranberries plated on a @feltandfat Azul serving tray.
Mood.

Since I am sick and both my partner and I missed out on visiting family today, I am going to pretend this is the look I wore.
